title: For Sale/Trade:  M35 beretta 1944
postcontent:
**ww2 beretta model 1935  "m35"**
records indicate this beretta pistol was included in a delivery of 65,000 Beretta M1934/35 pistols delivered to the German Army Headquarters in Italy between Aug 1944 and Feb, 1945. Those serial # were 534000/599000.- "mine has #'s in that range"
 After the 8 September 1943 armistice between Italy and the Allies, the Germans saddled Beretta with three engineers from Germany. Moreover the factory was GARRISONED BY THE SS! Weapons of that time, even the ones produced for the Germans, bore the punch mark 4UT, (Quarto Ufficio tecnico di Controllo Armi e Munizioni--4th Technnical Control Unit...
-an C. Still, in Axis Pistols, page 107, states,
"It is likely that almost all of the 4/UT, ...were used by the German Army". He also includes two other variations in this statement, "1944 dated and blank slide Model 1935".
Ugo Menchini, in Pietro Beretta Le Automatiche, regarding an M1934, page 255, states,
"In late 1940 there appears an oval including the punch mark IVU. It refers to the 4th technical Control Unit of the FAG, where inspection was carried out."
 Note that, while they seem to represent the same inspectors, the "IVU" is not the same mark as the "4UT". The IVU would be found on the pre RSI model M1934, and the 4UT would be found on the RSI model M1935.
 These are the reasons why I believe that it is likely that all of the 4UT Berettas WERE RSI pistols!! the IVU and the 4UT were the same office, but under Italian management -the IVU, before the surrender of Italy, and German the 4UT, so after september, 8 1943.

 Near mint unissued condition, mint crown & mirror bore with hardly any wear on the internals, no rust or rust pitting. parkerized late war model, with tooling and machinery marks throughout. one extra period magazine very unique & presentable for the ww2 weapons collector!   FTF PERMIT OR VALID STATE IDENTIFICATION REQUIRED.  720 620 78 84

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Model of 1905
postcontent:
I've got a Smith & Wesson Model of 1905 4th change, also known as the Military and Police, chambered in .38spl.  Serial number places its build date between 1919 and 1921, meaning it was one of the earliest models to feature a heat treated cylinder. Includes original checkered wood grips and Pachmayr rubber grips.

Action is butter smooth and solid, lockup is fine, and the trigger is sublime at about 3.5 lbs. It's an accurate and sweet shooting gun. Barrel is dark and shows a very small amount of pitting, but the rifling is still going strong.  
The nickel finish is in rough shape, but there is zero rust on the gun.

This is truly a great shooter with a lot of character, and is in excellent shape considering its age. Almost a century old and still rock solid and dependable from a time where things were built to last.
I'm not too intent on getting rid of it but wanted to see what I could get.

More high quality pictures of it can be found here: http://imgur.com/a/ctOXQ

PSL-54C / FPK Dragunov - Unfired - Complete w/Accessories
 Older hand select Romanian PSL-54C demill kit built by / on Tennessee Guns Int'l receiver. Front trunnion is a specified screw build with the remainder being the standard riveted TGI receiver assembly. It has been properly headspaced / drilled, lubed and 'tuned', but has never been fired. There was also a reinforced swivel stud installed on the lower handguard specifically for a bipod. A bipod, Plano foam padded case and a TGI manual included as well. Basically, a complete PSL rifle package and as 'new' as you can get.

 All accessories for this PSL / FPK are either new, unissued or unused, as originally received from TGI and  include:

3-piece cleaning rod
4 mag capacity field pouch
Two magazines (1 is unnumbered)
Romanian TIP2 6x24 side rail mounted scope
Scope cover
Scope cleaning cloth
Yellow scope lens filter

 The cleaning kit has all of the usual parts. A 7.62x54R extractor, gas port reamer, cleaning jag, brush, pin tool, grease bottle, tube / cap and a nice black pouch to keep all of it in, PLUS a spare sight post, extractor retaining pin, spring and a firing pin retainer. It all fits in the field pouch, which has multiple pockets inside and out.

 All of the serial numbered components on the rifle match, except for the bolt itself and the made in Romania TGI receiver serial number. It is the original Romanian chrome lined barrel with sharp rifling and it's mirror bright. It has the matching numbered threaded muzzle device (14x1mm LH) and the intact bayonet lug. The earlier TGI contracted receivers included the bolt hold open center support piece, but do NOT include the little parts (spring, pin and lifter foot, etc.). postcontent: Here's a very nice Fox AE 20 gauge with 30" long, 3 weight barrels choked F/IM. This gun was built in 1921 and is in very good condition (see pictures).  It weighs 6 pounds 1 ounce on my postal scale, has 2 1/2" chambers, a 14" LOP to a replacement pad, a 1 5/8" drop at comb, and 2 5/8" drop at heel. It does not appear to have any cast. The blueing is in very good condition and is original. The wood is in great shape, as is the checkering; however, there is a small hairline crack just behind the receiver on one side - it has been there a long time and has not changed despite shooting the gun a number of times. There are no dents or scratches in the wood, only one small crack as noted earlier. There is one spot on the barrels where the blueing is slightly scratched from use (this is shown in the pictures). There are slight case colors on the receiver. The gun locks up very tight and the open lever is slightly to the right, indicating it hasn't seen very extensive use. The ejectors work perfectly. This is a great example of a nice grade Fox small bore with desirable 30" barrels in great condition.  I would price this gun significantly higher if it didn't have the small crack in the stock.  I have many more pictures I can send - just let me know if you want them.
